solution:
Three collections: **orchestras**, **persons** (holding both Maestro and Musician documents, distinguished by a `role` field, since they share the same shape and Person super-type), and **instruments**. Instrument is kept as its own small, mostly-static reference collection because it is referenced by many musicians (many-to-many) and rarely changes.

Relations:
- Maestro–Orchestra (1,1)-(1,1): embed the director directly inside the orchestra document, or keep a `directorId` reference on the orchestra (since it's 1:1, embedding is natural).
- Orchestra–Musician (10..N)-(1,2): reference-based (a musician can belong to up to 2 orchestras, so it cannot be embedded one-sidedly); store an array of `orchestraIds` in the musician document.
- Musician–Instrument (1..N)-(1..N): embed a small array of subdocuments `{ instrumentId, name, since }` inside the musician document, since instruments-played is bounded and read together with the musician.

```json
// orchestras
{ "_id": "orc1", "name": "Filarmonica", "foundationDate": "1900-01-01", "biography": "...",
  "director": { "personalId": "m1", "name": "Claudio", "stageName": "..." } }

// persons (role: "Musician")
{ "_id": "p1", "role": "Musician", "name": "Fabiana", "surname": "...", "biography": "...",
  "orchestraIds": ["orc1"],
  "instruments": [ { "instrumentId": "i1", "name": "Piano", "since": "2015-01-01" } ] }

// instruments
{ "_id": "i1", "name": "Piano", "type": "chordophone/percussion", "description": "..." }
```

```javascript
db.persons.aggregate([
  { $match: { role: "Musician" } },
  { $unwind: "$orchestraIds" },
  { $unwind: "$instruments" },
  { $group: {
      _id: { orchestraId: "$orchestraIds", instrument: "$instruments.name" },
      musicianCount: { $sum: 1 }
  }},
  { $match: { musicianCount: { $gte: 3 } } },
  { $group: {
      _id: "$_id.orchestraId",
      instrumentsWithEnoughMusicians: { $sum: 1 }
  }},
  { $match: { instrumentsWithEnoughMusicians: { $gte: 4 } } }
])
```

Step by step: unwind each musician's orchestras and instruments to get one row per (musician, orchestra, instrument); group by (orchestra, instrument) counting distinct musicians; keep only (orchestra, instrument) pairs with at least 3 musicians; regroup by orchestra counting how many such instruments qualify; keep orchestras with at least 4 qualifying instruments.

```javascript
db.orchestras.aggregate([
  { $match: { "director.name": "Claudio" } },
  { $lookup: {
      from: "persons",
      let: { orcId: "$_id" },
      pipeline: [
        { $match: {
            $expr: { $in: ["$$orcId", "$orchestraIds"] },
            role: "Musician",
            name: "Lorenzo",
            "instruments.name": "Piano"
        }}
      ],
      as: "matchingMembers"
  }},
  { $match: { "matchingMembers.0": { $exists: true } } },
  { $count: "numOrchestras" }
])
```

Filter orchestras directed by "Claudio"; for each, `$lookup` the musicians belonging to that orchestra who are named "Lorenzo" and play the piano; keep orchestras that found at least one such member; `$count` the survivors.

```
PUT /tracks
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "title":     { "type": "text" },
      "duration":  { "type": "integer" },
      "composer":  { "type": "keyword" },
      "musicType": { "type": "keyword" }
    }
  }
}
```

`title` is mapped as `text` since it should support full-text search/analysis; `composer` and `musicType` are mapped as `keyword` because they are used for exact-match filtering and aggregation (not analyzed free text); `duration` is a numeric `integer` field to support range queries.

```
GET /tracks/_search
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "filter": [
        { "term":  { "composer":  "Bach" } },
        { "range": { "duration":  { "gt": 8 } } },
        { "term":  { "musicType": "classical" } }
      ],
      "should": [
        { "range": { "duration": { "gt": 11 } } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

All three hard conditions (composer = "Bach", duration > 8, musicType = "classical") go into `filter`, which is applied in a non-scoring context (a `bool` filter context contributes no score, only inclusion/exclusion), so the composer clause cannot affect ranking. The `duration > 11` condition is placed in `should`, which does contribute to the relevance score when matched, so documents lasting more than 11 minutes are boosted/prioritized above the rest of the matches without being required.
